content:
TV Asahi reports on this year's "Halloween Martial Law" in Shanghai
In Shanghai, China, Halloween costume events in the city center are held as scheduled at this time of year, but this year, the authorities have cracked down on this activity.
In previous years, during Halloween, the area was always bustling with citizens dressed as various characters. However, this year, several citizens were prevented from entering the store by the police due to wearing cosplay (role-playing costumes).
A woman dressed as a character said: "This year, cosplay is banned. It is said that there are too many people to prevent stampedes. But maybe it's because it's a Japanese character. Everyone is "patriotic."
Some media reported that the Shanghai authorities have issued a notice during Halloween to ban cosplay in the city center.
An employee of a store confirmed: "The police verbally informed us of these regulations."
In the past, some people also wore anti-epidemic clothing or imitated street...
fullContent:
朝日电视台报道了今年的上海“万圣节戒严”事件
在中国上海，每年这个时候，市中心的万圣节变装活动都会如期举行，但今年，当局对这一活动进行了打压。
往年，在万圣节期间，这个地区总是热闹非凡，充满了装扮成各种角色的市民。然而今年，由于穿着 cosplay（角色扮演服装），多名市民被警方阻止进入商店。
一名装扮成角色的女性表示：“今年说是禁止 cosplay，据说是因为人多，为了防止踩踏事故。但也许是因为这是日本的角色吧。大家都‘爱国’。”
有些媒体报道说，上海市当局已在万圣节期间发布通知，禁止在市中心进行角色扮演。
一家商店的员工证实：“警察有口头通知我们这些规定。”
过去，也有人穿防疫服装或模仿街头安装的“监控摄像头”等讽刺政府的装扮，因此当局可能对此类活动格外敏感。
